===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To be saturated with liquid by being immersed in it.
#: ''I'm going to '''soak''' in the bath for a couple of hours.''
#* Bible, Isa. xxiv. 7
#*: Their land shall be '''soaked''' with blood.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To [[immerse]] in [[liquid]] to the point of saturation or thorough permeation.
#: '''''Soak''' the beans overnight before cooking.''
# {{context|intransitive|lang=en}} To [[penetrate]] or [[permeate]] by saturation.
#: ''The water '''soaked''' into my shoes and gave me wet feet.''
#* Sir Walter Scott
#*: The rivulet beneath '''soaked''' its way obscurely through wreaths of snow.
# {{context|transitive|lang=en}} To allow (especially a liquid) to be absorbed; to take in, receive. (''usually + '''[[up]]''''')
#: ''A sponge '''soaks''' up water; the skin '''soaks''' in moisture.''
#: ''I '''soaked''' up all the knowledge I could at university.''
# {{context|slang|dated|lang=en}} To [[drink]] [[intemperate]]ly or [[gluttonous]]ly.
# {{context|metallurgy|lang=en}} To heat a metal before shaping it.
# {{context|ceramics|lang=en}} To hold a kiln at a particular temperature for a given period of time.
#: ''We should '''soak''' the kiln at cone 9 for half an hour.''
# {{context|figurative|lang=en}} To [[absorb]]; to [[drain]].
#: {{rfquotek|Sir H. Wotton}}

